          <msContents>
            <summary>
              <p>Single parchment folio; Shelfmark: HC.MS.03224; Qurʾānic Text: Q  10:28-10:33; Lines per page: 8-10; Dimensions: 191 x 193 mm; Script  style: Maġribī chrysography, interlaced angular script (for <hi rend="italic">sūra </hi>titles); Estimated date of production: Late 13th or 14th century; Provenance: Northwest Africa (Maġrib) or Muslim Iberia (al-Andalus).</p>
              <p> </p>
              <p>  </p>
              <p>The manuscript is unlikely to have been entirely written in gold: the chrysography was probably meant to signal the end of the 21st and beginning of the 22nd <hi rend="italic">ḥizb </hi>(here placed after 10:33, although it should be after 10:25). The <hi rend="italic">taʿawwuḏ </hi>was added in an illuminated heading and written in an elaborate interlaced Kufic reminiscent of Marinid and Nasrid epigraphy from the first half of the 14th century. Yellow/orange dots mark the <hi rend="italic">hamza </hi>above or below <hi rend="italic">alif</hi>. The symbols of <hi rend="italic">sukūn </hi>and <hi rend="italic">tašdīd </hi>are traced in blue, in contrast with all the other vocalisation marks, which are in red. A portion of a similar manuscript, partially written in Maġribī chrysography (although with 11 lines per page) is in New York, Metropolitan Museum of Art, Inv. 2004.90.</p>
            </summary>
